Wale Oyewale, Ibadan The Deputy Governor of Oyo State, Rauf Olaniyan, has urged the people of Oyo and Ogun states not to allow boundary dispute to upset the healthy relationship between them as sister states. Olaniyan, who was represented by the Surveyor-General of Oyo State, Abiodun Alaba, said the two states should reach an amicable resolution and leverage on the opportunities of their closeness. He made the appeal at the verification meeting held at the office of the Deputy Governor of Ogun State, Oke-Mosan, Abeokuta. Earlier in her address, the Deputy Governor of Ogun State, Noimot Salako-Oyedele, advised the affected residents to embrace peace in an effort to address problems arising from the disputed areas. Representatives of the Director-General, National Boundary Commission, Ugbah Chinma, and that of the Surveyor-General of the Federation, Adebomehin Adeyemi, said  they were at the meeting to ascertain the technical discrepancies in the interstate boundary. It was agreed that a new date for the technical committee meeting in Abuja would be communicated to the concerned parties for resolution. The National Boundary Commission had conducted field verification of the disputed areas to check the reported technical discrepancies observed in the conversion of the affected area from imperial to metric units in some sectors of the previously resolved interstate boundary dispute. ”Copyright PUNCH.
